cards.helptext:
This card holds all of the information necessary to locate the physical, legal document in which the conservation easement is recorded.

Conservation easements are recorded like deeds.In Utah, each county has a recorder's office. The County Recorder records and maintains all documents pertaining to real estate property in their county  and maintains cross-reference indexes to these records. The Recorder's Office is also required to maintain a set of maps which show the current ownership of every tract of land in the entire county.

Documents such as deeds and conservation easements are cited using a standard system of identifying the County Recorder, the Book, and the starting page on which the document begins.

For example, Duchesne County Book 18 Page 452 may commonly be abbreviated as Duchesne 18/452. If you have a citation like the latter, the number before the / is the Book and the number after the slash is the page number.

Even if the document is multiple pages, only list the first page.
cards.name: Easement Legal Documentation

cards.helptext:
This card holds all of the information necessary to locate the physical, legal document in which the conservation easement's amendment is recorded.

Conservation easements are recorded like deeds.In Utah, each county has a recorder's office. The County Recorder records and maintains all documents pertaining to real estate property in their county  and maintains cross-reference indexes to these records. The Recorder's Office is also required to maintain a set of maps which show the current ownership of every tract of land in the entire county.

Documents such as deeds and conservation easements are cited using a standard system of identifying the County Recorder, the Book, and the starting page on which the document begins.

For example, Duchesne County Book 18 Page 452 may commonly be abbreviated as Duchesne 18/452. If you have a citation like the latter, the number before the / is the Book and the number after the slash is the page number.

Even if the document is multiple pages, only list the first page.

cards.helptext:
Why was this property important to conserve? The statement of significance is an opportunity to document the justification for the conservation easement and to communicate to the public why this property is special.

In cases where the property is on the state or national register, you may want to refer to its narrative statement of significance as recorded by the relevant agencies.
cards.name: Statement of Significance

cards.helptext:
Use this card to record as many actors that are related to the easement as necessary.

An actor may be an individual or a group (such as a Trust, business, NGO, or government entity). 

Enter the entity's name in the Entity field. If they have not been entered into Arches yet, you will have the option to Create a New Actor.
cards.name: Easement Entities

cards.description: The features of this property that covered by the easement.
cards.helptext:
Many properties have several features (or elements); for instance, a propery may have two buildings: a single family dwelling and a detached garage. In this card, you can record all of the features on the property that are subject to the conservation easement. 

First, choose whether the element is a building, part of the grounds, or an interior room.

Then, identify the feature. In the case of an easement that covers one building, you can leave the feature name blank or use the name of the property itself.

Enter the built date using EDTF -- Extended Date Time Format -- Standard of the Library of Congress. These are some common EDTF date styles:

  • 1985-04-12 (if you know the exact date)
  • 1985-04 (if you know the month and year)
  • 1985 (if you know the year)
  • 1984? (if you are uncertain of the year)
  • 2004~ (same as c. 2004)
  • 2004-04~ (same as c. April 2004)
  • 184X (some time in 1840s)
  • 18XX (some time in 19th century)

Choose an architectural style from the list. Be consistent in usage. You may want to look at the SHPOs site file to see how they've classified the building.

Enter as many materials as needed by selecting them from the list, one by one. You don't need to enter every single material -- just the ones that are pertinent to the easement.
cards.instructions: Features or elements on the property subject to the conservation easement
cards.name: Property Features

cards.helptext:
Enter all of the names that this property has carried. Use the +New button to add multiple names.

Every property must have a "Current, preferred" name. This should be the name that Preservation Utah uses to refer to the property.

Only enter a historic or other known name if they are in addition to the current, preferred name. A historic name is one that was used historically, but is no longer in common parlance. An other known name is an alternative name that local community members may use.
cards.name: Property Name

cards.helptext:
This is where you may enter all of the functions that you have been able to document about this property. 

Functions may either be "current" (i.e. the property is still used for this purpose) or "historic" (i.e. the property once was used for this purpose, but is no longer.)

There may be multiple current functions as well as multple historic functions. You may expand upon some of these functions in the property's statement of significance.

For instance, the Old Post Office in Washington DC would have a current function of hotel, but several historic functions, including post office, and government office.
cards.name: Function
